    "created_at": "2024-03-08T12:14:09Z",
    "updated_at": "2024-03-08T12:16:12Z",
    "body": "Imagine you download and extract just some archive from a malicious website, then step into the extracted folder.\r\n\r\n> Like how else would we figure out something is \"an actual version of Python\".\r\n\r\nI don't know how you would. Personally, I'm handling venvs differently in my config:\r\nI'm only showing a venv symbol when a `pyvenv.cfg` file gets detected in a folder, and I'm showing the Python version only for activated venvs with a standard `python -V` (where activation gets detected based on the VIRTUAL_ENV env variable).\r\nMy idea is that by activating the venv I'm actively taking a decision about the thing's safety, which I'm not doing by just stepping into the folder.",
    "author_association": "NONE",
    "pin": null,
